---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '@/components/ui/PageHeader.astro';
import LifecycleEvents from '@/components/react/LifecycleEvents.tsx';
import ValueTable from '@/components/ui/ValueTable.astro';
import Callout from '@/components/ui/Callout.astro';
import DocRef from '@/components/ui/DocRef.astro';
import { NMAS_TABLE, CPKS_TABLE } from '@/data/tables';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Status & lifecycle events"
  description="How OSNMA renews and revokes chains, keys and the Merkle tree — and what the receiver does."
>
  <PageHeader
    eyebrow="6 · Key & lifecycle management"
    title="Status and lifecycle events"
    lead="Keys and chains do not last forever. OSNMA renews and revokes them on the fly, announcing each event in the header so receivers stay authenticated through the change."
  />

  <p>
    Two header fields drive everything here. <strong>NMAS</strong> says whether the
    service is usable; <strong>CPKS</strong> announces which lifecycle event, if
    any, is in progress <DocRef doc="icd" section="3.1" />. Together they tell a
    receiver exactly what to do.
  </p>

  <ValueTable table={NMAS_TABLE} />
  <ValueTable table={CPKS_TABLE} />

  <h2>The six events</h2>
  <p>
    Each CPKS value beyond Nominal is a managed transition. Some keep the service
    Operational throughout (renewals); others pass through "Don't use" while
    something is revoked. Pick an event to see its phases and the receiver actions —
    each mapped to the official test-vector scenario that reproduces it
    <DocRef doc="rxg" section="4.2" />:
  </p>

  <LifecycleEvents client:visible />

  <h2>The pattern</h2>
  <p>
    Renewals (EOC, NPK, NMT) overlap the old and new material so authentication
    never stops: the replacement is broadcast and verified <em>before</em> it takes
    over. Revocations (CREV, PKREV) cannot do that — the compromised material must
    go immediately — so the service drops to "Don't use" until a trustworthy
    replacement is in force. The alert (OAM) is the hard stop: discard everything
    and reconnect to the GSC server.
  </p>

  <Callout type="security">
    <p>
      Every one of these signals is authenticated — CPKS and NMAS are covered by the
      DSM-KROOT signature the receiver re-verifies at least hourly. A spoofer cannot
      force a receiver into "Don't use" or trick it into accepting revoked keys.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <Callout type="note">
    <p>
      A receiver returning from a long sleep may have missed an entire event. That
      is why start-up re-checks PKID and CID against what it has stored — see
      <a href="/receiver/startup">cold / warm / hot start</a>.
    </p>
  </Callout>
</BaseLayout>
